Supervised machine learning (ML) using R

Summary

The goal is to analyse the Breast Cancer Wisconsin Data Set using a variety of supervised ML methods.

ML methods

These are the individual methods we will use:

  • Decision Tree Classifier
  • Naive Bayes
  • k-nearest Neighbors
  • Random Forest
  • SVM: support-vector machines
  • Linear Discriminant Analysis

Analysis

R libraries

We need a couple of libraries for the exercises. Lets load them all upfront:

library(ggplot2)
library(reshape2)
library(caret)
library(rpart.plot)
library(class)
library(randomForest)
library(pander)
library(kernlab)

Data Exploration

Load the data

df=read.table("data.csv.gz", header=T, sep=",")
df$outcome = factor(df$outcome)   # Outcome is a categorical variable

Summarize the data set

ggplot(data=df, aes(x=outcome, y=mean.radius)) + geom_boxplot(aes(group=outcome))

ggplot(data=df, aes(x=outcome, y=worst.area)) + geom_boxplot(aes(group=outcome))

Plot all features at once

lf = melt(df, id=c("outcome"))
ggplot(data=lf, aes(x=outcome, y=value)) +
    geom_boxplot(aes(group=outcome)) +
    facet_wrap(~variable, scales="free_y")

ggplot(data=lf, aes(x=value)) +
    geom_freqpoly(aes(group=outcome, color=outcome), stat="bin", bins=30) +
    facet_wrap(~variable, scales="free")

Splitting Training and Testing data

The dimensions of the data matrix are 31 columns and 569 rows.

print(dim(df))
## [1] 569  31

One column is the outcome (1: malignant and 0: benign) and the remaining columns are 30 features. Each row is one patient record. We first split the data into a training and testing set.

set.seed(3033)
train = createDataPartition(y = df$outcome, p=0.8, list=F)
training = df[train,]
print(dim(training))
## [1] 456  31
testing = df[-train,]
print(dim(testing))
## [1] 113  31
pander(table(training$outcome), caption="Training outcome distribution")
Training outcome distribution
0 1
170 286 
pander(table(testing$outcome), caption="Testing outcome distribution")
Testing outcome distribution
0 1
42 71

Decision Tree Classifier

trctrl = trainControl(method="repeatedcv", number=10, repeats=3)
fit = train(outcome ~ ., data=training, method="rpart", parms = list(split="information"), trControl=trctrl, tuneLength=10)
prp(fit$finalModel, tweak=1.2)

pred = predict(fit, newdata=testing)

Lets take a look at the confusion matrix:

cm <- table(data.frame(prediction=pred, truth=testing$outcome))
pander(cm, caption="Confusion Matrix for Decision Tree")
Confusion Matrix for Decision Tree
0 1
0 38 4
1 4 67

Naive Bayes

fit = train(outcome ~ ., data=training, method="naive_bayes", trControl=trctrl, tuneLength=10)
pred = predict(fit, newdata=testing)
cm <- table(data.frame(prediction=pred, truth=testing$outcome))
pander(cm, caption="Confusion Matrix for Naive Bayes")

Questions

A couple of question for yourself to explore the data further.

  • What is the true positive rate (sensitivity) for each method?
  • What is the true negative rate (specificity) for each method?
  • What is the precision (positive predictive value) for each method?
  • What is the false discovery rate (FDR) for each method?
  • What is the accuracy for each method?
